<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 2:10<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2561f160630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>2.</label.designator><headtext>Witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I257d4190630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.designator>B.</label.designator><headtext>Competency</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05c5682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>2:10.</label.designator><headtext>Physical capacity</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The witness must be able to communicate his testimony to the jury in some fashion, but no physical defect in any of the senses shall incapacitate a witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic17f11407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] For example, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-serial-number="1972127383" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id24a30a27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Hensley v. State</ital></cite.query>, the deaf-mute victim of a robbery testified through an interpreter.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic17f11417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-serial-number="1982108103" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id24af3f27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Reed v. State</ital></cite.query>, the speech-impaired witness testified through an interpreter.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic17f38507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-serial-number="1986126786" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id24bb7427fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Grant v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic17f38517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] a deaf-mute 12-year-old victim testified through two sign-language interpreters. <eos/><bos/>However, physical impairment due to alcohol[<footnote.reference refid="Ic17f38527fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] or drug consumption[<footnote.reference refid="Ic17f5f607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] may affect a witness&apos; competency.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The American with Disabilities Act (ADA), which Congress passed in 1990, ensures equal opportunity for people with disabilities. <eos/><bos/>Under the ADA and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-604" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id24e01307fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-604</cite.query>, Georgia courts are required to provide a qualified sign language interpreter to deaf or hard of hearing individuals. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-604" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id24e01317fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-604</cite.query> also includes foreign language interpretation. <eos/><bos/>The use of an interpreter in federal practice is governed by <cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER604" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Id24e01327fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 604</cite.query>, which provides that <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“(a)n interpreter is subject to the provisions of these rules relating to qualification as an expert and the <page no="14"/>administration of an oath or affirmation to make a true translation.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/> <cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRCRPR28" w-pub-number="1000598" ID="Id24e01337fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Crim. P. 28</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRCPR43" w-pub-number="1000600" ID="Id24e01347fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Civ. P. 43(d)</cite.query> provide that the court may appoint an interpreter of its own selection and determine the compensation such interpreter will receive. <eos/><bos/>In criminal cases, the funds for interpreter compensation must be provided by law or by the government as provided by the court. <eos/><bos/>In civil cases, the compensation may be paid from funds provided by law or by one or more parties, and the court may tax the compensation as costs.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic17f11407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-604" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id2496d507fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-604</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic17f11417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-serial-number="1972127383" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id24a7ec27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Hensley v. State, 228 Ga. 501, 186 S.E.2d 729 (1972)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic17f38507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-serial-number="1982108103" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id24b42127fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Reed v. State, 249 Ga. 52, 287 S.E.2d 205 (1982)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic17f38517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-serial-number="1986126786" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id24bde527fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Grant v. State, 178 Ga. App. 398, 343 S.E.2d 422 (1986)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic17f38527fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-serial-number="1966132085" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id24c7a927fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Whitus v. State, 222 Ga. 103, 149 S.E.2d 130 (1966)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d on other grounds</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-serial-number="1967129463" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Id24c7a957fbf11ea988285db8533e975">385 U.S. 545, 87 S. Ct. 643, 17 L. Ed. 2d 599 (1967)</cite.query>, the court held that evidence that a witness was in a drunken condition when he undertook to testify goes to competency and proof that he was drunk on the occasion about which he testified goes to his credibility.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic17f5f607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018083" w-serial-number="1974127546" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id24cefc27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Geter v. State, 231 Ga. 615, 203 S.E.2d 195 (1974)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="14"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 2:10<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
